    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor addresses variability arising from biological specimen-to-specimen variation (e.g., donor-to-donor variability in red blood cell fragility) that is relevant when physical hemolysis testing uses actual blood from multiple donors. In this COU, the validation experiments use a well-characterized glycerol-water blood analog fluid (not donor blood), and the CFD model does not represent inter-donor biological variability. Specimen sampling statistics are therefore not applicable to either the computational model or its validation evidence base. This factor is formally scoped out of the MRL 2 assessment for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor is applicable when a computational model is being used as a substitute for a physical test to demonstrate device equivalence to a predicate, requiring demonstration that the simulation inputs are equivalent to the predicate device's inputs. In this COU, the model is used to identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions within the design space of a single device variant, not to establish equivalence between two distinct devices or to substitute for a regulatory predicate comparison. The equivalency assessment is performed at the system level using the relative hemolysis index (RH) comparison, which is addressed under the Output Comparison factor. No separate factor-level equivalency of input parameters assessment is therefore warranted."
    }
